PRETORIA &#8211; New South African Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba said on Saturday he was committed to maintaining South Africa&#8217;s investment-grade credit ratings, which analysts have said are threatened after the removal of his predecessor Pravin Gordhan.Addressing a news conference, Gigaba also signaled a shift to the left, saying &#8220;we need to radically transform the South African economy&#8221;.President Jacob Zuma&#8217;s midnight sacking of Gordhan shook South African markets on Friday, undermining his authority and threatening to split the African National Congress that has governed since the end of apartheid. 